Over my past 11 years coaching several hundred people from dozens of organi=
zations and teaching thousands more, there=E2=80=99s one challenge I=E2=80=
=99ve seen people struggle with across every level, industry, company stage=
, personality type, and culture: giving feedback.
Many people come to coaching and workshops already describing themselves as=
 =E2=80=9Cconflict-averse,=E2=80=9D dreading having difficult conversations=
 and giving direct feedback. A good number arrive fed up with failed attemp=
ts to get people to change their behavior, with many missing the irony as t=
hey bemoan, =E2=80=9CI keep giving them the same feedback, and they never c=
hange. Maybe they just don=E2=80=99t want to.=E2=80=9D
What these folks miss is their own power to catalyze change by shifting the=
 framing and approach of the feedback they give.
I=E2=80=99ve seen and felt firsthand the difference between the =E2=80=9Cfe=
edback masters=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cfeedback disasters.=E2=80=9D After eve=
ry feedback conversation from one colleague who I had initially respected, =
I felt deflated. As a result, everything suffered: our product, our relatio=
nship, and my overall well-being.
Later, I worked with another colleague whose feedback left me elated every =
time (actually!). I couldn=E2=80=99t wait for meetings with her because I e=
njoyed them so much and I knew that her feedback would help even my best wo=
rk reach another level.
On reflection, I realized that the content of the feedback from these two c=
olleagues was strikingly similar, but the way my second colleague framed an=
d delivered hers lifted me up instead of shutting me down.
That difference answered an age-old question: How on earth do you get someo=
ne to change or grow? And how can you do that in ways that strengthen your =
