ccess is my brilliance, what does that imply about the cause of my potentia=
l failures? This is especially pernicious in contexts that require experime=
ntation, where failure=E2=80=94however temporary=E2=80=94is inevitable. Thi=
s dynamic is exacerbated when the flattering judgments come from a manager =
or executive.
That rockstar PM=E2=80=99s focus reorients from iteration and impact to see=
king approval.
She could spend a lot of energy trying to get an =E2=80=9CExceeds Expectati=
ons=E2=80=9D on her next report card=E2=80=94I mean performance review=E2=
=80=94instead of focusing on influencing user behavior or being more effect=
ive in her work relationships.
By contrast, observations of people=E2=80=99s actions and impacts point the=
m to what is within their control=E2=80=94the actions they can change or ke=
ep doing and the potential impacts of those actions. They see how to increa=
se their own ability to create their desired outcomes. This means that givi=
ng this kind of actionable feedback can actually evoke feedback recipients=
=E2=80=99 growth mindsets, or as Satya Nadella frames it [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/ee5657a0-6d13-4132-b09=
0-224ed13f6e2d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiNWtiOTN6In0.=
zdzy88YFxPmLQJf9hshgUC7BDnPG6RxQ4tAjMRMPOw0 ], help them shift from know-it=
-alls to learn-it-alls. If you want greater openness and motivation, share =
impacts, not judgments! Here=E2=80=99s how [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
011c5357-6c94-4859-9022-6a11b28eefad?j=3DeyJ1IjoiNWtiOTN6In0.zdzy88YFxPmLQJ=
f9hshgUC7BDnPG6RxQ4tAjMRMPOw0 ].
Acknowledge your own actions and their impacts
Judgments aren=E2=80=99t the only trigger for defensiveness. When you as th=
e feedback giver have contributed to a situation but you aren=E2=80=99t not=
ing that, the recipient=E2=80=99s attention can latch onto this gap. =E2=80=
=9CYeah, but what about your actions?=E2=80=9D they wonder. You can preempt=
 this reaction by simply and directly acknowledging your contribution.
As a social species, humans unconsciously mirror the behavior we see in oth=
ers around us. The crowd waits at a light, and so do we; we start jaywalkin=
g, and others are more likely to as well. This plays out interpersonally to=
o. Far too often, we approach feedback conversations with the implicit atti=
tude of =E2=80=9CYou are the one who needs to change.=E2=80=9D From this an=
gle, it=E2=80=99s no surprise that what we get back is the other person loo=
king at us thinking, =E2=80=9CNo, you are the one who needs to change.=E2=
=80=9D We tend to get what we give.
But this human instinct is actually good news: if you want to lead a conver=
sation and a relationship in a specific direction, just start moving in tha=
t direction yourself. The message switches to =E2=80=9CI think we can both =
shift some things that will make it easier to change and move toward that G=
oal.=E2=80=9D
This is one of most disarming feedback approaches I=E2=80=99ve ever encount=
ered=E2=80=94and one of the least-used. Once we have acknowledged our contr=
ibution and shown that we are monitoring our own behavior, the other person=
 can release their focus on our actions, freeing up their attention to conc=
entrate on their own actions.
There=E2=80=99s an added benefit here for the feedback giver: shifts that I=
 make in one relationship often apply to other relationships too. When I wa=
s frustrated with one client constantly rescheduling, I realized how I was =
contributing to and even encouraging the problem by always saying yes to re=
quests. Quick check-ins with all my clients around minimizing changes dropp=
ed rescheduling requests to zero across the board. More levers, more levera=
ge.
N: Next actions
What do we do with those levers we identified? Once feedback has been share=
d and received, the final step in an effective feedback conversation is def=
ining next actions. These could be actions for the feedback recipient, the =
feedback giver, or both.
The clearer and more concrete our action-and-impact observations are, the m=
ore obvious the potential next actions become.
Sometimes it=E2=80=99s a very direct link: =E2=80=9CHey, when you don=E2=80=
=99t schedule interviews in the time frame you said you would, it slows dow=
n our hiring process. Can you schedule those this week and let me know if t=
here are any blockers?=E2=80=9D
Other times, arriving at next actions is more complex and uncomfortable. Ou=
r insides are screaming, =E2=80=9CThis conversation is awkward. Get me out =
of here already!=E2=80=9D But even an otherwise-great feedback conversation=
 will often amount to nothing if we don=E2=80=99t close it clearly and conc=
retely.
There are a few ways of doing this that increase buy-in and follow-through.
First, ask for their ideas
In an often-maddening phenomenon, people will resist change that they thems=
elves want if it appears to come at the expense of their autonomy. We may w=
ant to change, but we want to choose it.
One simple way of supporting someone=E2=80=99s sense of autonomy is to ask =
for their ideas of what to change before offering our own. When the other p=
erson is really on board with the Goal and open to hearing what we=E2=80=99=
ve shared, given even a few moments of brainstorming, I have found that the=
y regularly come up with useful options I had not considered. They also ten=
d to be more motivated to pursue ideas they have generated themselves.
For feedback that is difficult to hear regardless of how it=E2=80=99s share=
d, a feedback conversation might actually be a series of conversations, so =
it=E2=80=99s often best to sleep on it and schedule a future time to return=
 and commit to next actions (not just =E2=80=9Clater=E2=80=9D).
Co-create through brainstorming together
If you are itching to share your own idea but also want to involve them, th=
is option opens up the opportunity for both. It also lets you build on each=
 other=E2=80=99s ideas.
Make specific requests=E2=80=94and make it easy to say no
Sometimes asking for the other person=E2=80=99s ideas can feel disingenuous=
 when all you want is to propose your own. In that case, share your idea, a=
nd offer it as a suggestion or a request in a way that still honors their a=
utonomy=E2=80=94in other words, not as a demand.
To support this feeling, make it easy for them to say no to or edit the req=
uest. A meta-analysis [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e189fd9-fa7b-40c2-a1=
08-c17f1fa0cac6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiNWtiOTN6In0.zdzy88YFxPmLQJf9hshgUC7BDnPG6RxQ4tA=
jMRMPOw0 ] of 52 studies showed that =E2=80=9CFeel free to say no=E2=80=9D =
doubled the percentage of time that people said yes to a request. Supportin=
g autonomy conveys real respect, which preempts resistance, engenders goodw=
ill, and helps people think clearly about the suggestion on its own merits.=
 If they actually say no, you will get to learn what=E2=80=99s blocking the=
m and how to incorporate that in the next actions. (And if you=E2=80=99re f=
eeling attached to your idea and actually want to demand it, remember that =
it=E2=80=99s the Goal you care about, not the way they get there.)
It=E2=80=99s also important to ensure that your specific request includes w=
hat you want more of, not just less of. As psychologist Marshall Rosenberg,=
 the author of Nonviolent Communication, said, =E2=80=9CYou can=E2=80=99t d=
o a don=E2=80=99t.=E2=80=9D Otherwise, when they find themselves in the sam=
e situation again, they=E2=80=99ll be unclear about what alternative behavi=
or to engage in.
Frame it as an experiment
When someone is considering a new behavior, that means there=E2=80=99s an e=
lement of uncertainty. Understandably, there can be some hesitance about co=
mmitting to do something they=E2=80=99ve never done before, no matter how m=
uch they follow the logic. Instead of committing to something new =E2=80=9C=
forever,=E2=80=9D explicitly acknowledge it as an experiment for a set time=
 period.
WWW: Who will do What by When?
This question moves growth, progress, and whole companies forward faster th=
an any other one I know.
=E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cshould=E2=80=9D are insidious =
impostors when it comes to action items. Let=E2=80=99s: Is that you or me? =
Should: Is that an idea we=E2=80=99re considering or a commitment? When you=
 hear these words, use them as an automatic signal to pause and clarify who=
 will do what by when.
Schedule a check-in
If you don=E2=80=99t set a clear check-in, you run the risk of not seeing t=
he change you were hoping for and having to initiate a follow-up feedback c=
onversation if you still want to close the gap. The discomfort of this is h=
igher, so it=E2=80=99s easier to avoid, and the frustration festers into re=
sentment and helplessness. If instead you establish a time and date to chec=
k in, you set up three more desirable possibilities:
An agreed-upon check-in time often increases the accountability and expecta=
tion of change.
The behavior may have changed, and you have a built-in moment to appreciate=
 the impacts you=E2=80=99re seeing and the progress toward the Goal, encour=
aging even more development. This reinforces a growth mindset.
If the behavior hasn=E2=80=99t changed or hasn=E2=80=99t had the desired im=
pact, you will recognize this sooner and be able to troubleshoot and course=
-correct faster.
AI in feedback
That=E2=80=99s a lot to digest and consider when preparing and leading a fe=
edback conversation. Fortunately, you=E2=80=99re not on your own anymore.
While many people fear AI will erode human connection, I see the opposite h=
appening with clients and in our workshops [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
a0bbb0ff-c3b9-4ead-a3f9-4f7472aa81c1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiNWtiOTN6In0.zdzy88YFxPmLQJ=
f9hshgUC7BDnPG6RxQ4tAjMRMPOw0 ]: People are using AI as a tool for expandin=
g interpersonal skills and deepening human relationships.
